# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bson-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bson-format/bson] The topmost element in the structure must be of type BSON object and contains 1 or more elements, where an element consists of a field name, a type, and a value.
[src:bson-format/bson] An important differentiator to JSON is that BSON contains types not present in JSON (e.g. datetime, byte array, and proper IEEE 754 floats) and offers type-strict handling for several numeric types instead of a universal "number" type.
[src:bson-format/bson] For situations where these additional types need to be represented in a textual way, MongoDB's Extended JSON format can be used.
[src:bson-format/bson] Compared to JSON, BSON is designed to be efficient both in storage space and scan-speed.
[src:bson-format/bson] Large elements in a BSON document are prefixed with a length field to facilitate scanning.
[src:bson-format/bson] In some cases, BSON will use more space than JSON due to the length prefixes and explicit array indices.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] Data exchange is similar to data integration except that data may be restructured with possible loss of content.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] There may be no way to transform a particular collection based on exchange constraints.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] Conversely, there may be multiple ways to transform the data, in which case one option must be identified in order to achieve compatibility between source and target.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] There are two main types of data exchange: broadcast and peer-to-peer (a.k.a. unicast).
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] For broadcast, data is transmitted simultaneously to all consumers.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] Just as a conference call, all participants get the same information from the speaker at the same time.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] For peer-to-peer, data is sent to a single receiver, defined by a specific address.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] For example, a letter goes to just one mail box.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] In some domains, a multiple source and target schema (proprietary data formats) may exist.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] An exchange or interchange format is often developed for a single domain, and then necessary routines (mappings) are written to (indirectly) transform/translate each and every source schema to each and every target schema by using the interchange format as an intermediate step.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] That requires less work than writing and debugging the many routines that would be required to directly translate each source schema directly to each target schema.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] A data exchange (a.k.a. interchange) language defines a domain-independent way to represent data.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] These languages have evolved from being markup and display-oriented to support the encoding of metadata that describes the structural attributes of the information.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] Practice has shown that certain types of formal languages are better suited for this task than others, since their specification is driven by a formal process instead of particular software implementation.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] For example, XML is a markup language that was designed to enable the creation of dialects (the definition of domain-specific sublanguages).
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] However, it does not contain domain-specific dictionaries or fact types.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] Beneficial to a reliable data exchange is the availability of standard dictionaries-taxonomies and tools libraries such as parsers, schema validators, and transformation tools.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] The popularity of XML for data exchange on the World Wide Web has several reasons.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] First of all, it is closely related to the preexisting standards Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML) and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML), and as such a parser written to support these two languages can be easily extended to support XML as well.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] For example, XHTML has been defined as a format that is formal XML, but understood correctly by most (if not all) HTML parsers.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] YAML was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor with notion similar to reStructuredText and wiki syntax.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] YAML 1.2 also includes a shorthand notion that is compatible with JSON, and as such any JSON document is also valid YAML; this however does not hold the other way.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] REBOL was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] It uses a simple free-form syntax with minimal punctuation and a rich set of data types (such as URL, email, date and time, tuple, string, tag) that respect common standards.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] It is designed to not need any additional meta-language, being designed in a metacircular fashion which is why the parse dialect used for definitions and transformations of REBOL dialects is also itself a dialect of REBOL.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] REBOL was used as a source of inspiration for JSON.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] The dictionary also includes standardized fact types.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] The terms and relation types together can be used to create and interpret expressions of facts, knowledge, requirements and other information.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] Gellish can be used in combination with SQL, RDF/XML, OWL and various other meta-languages.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] The Gellish standard is a combination of ISO 10303-221 (AP221) and ISO 15926.
[src:bson-format/data-exchange] The following describes and compares popular data exchange languages.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:bson-format/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In computing, **endianness** is the order in which bytes within a *word* data type are transmitted over a data communication medium or addressed in computer memory, counting only byte significance compared to earliness.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Endianness is primarily expressed as **big-endian** (**BE**) or **little-endian** (**LE**).
[src:bson-format/endianness] Computers store information in various-sized groups of binary bits.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Each group is assigned a number, called its *address*, that the computer uses to access that data.
[src:bson-format/endianness] On most modern computers, the smallest data group with an address is eight bits long, and is called a *byte*.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Larger groups comprise two or more bytes; for example, a *word* often contains 32 bits or 64 bits.
[src:bson-format/endianness] There are two principal ways a computer could number the individual bytes in a larger group, starting at either end.
[src:bson-format/endianness] A big-endian system stores the most significant byte of a word at the smallest memory address and the least significant byte at the largest.
[src:bson-format/endianness] A little-endian system, in contrast, stores the least-significant byte at the smallest address.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Of the two, big-endian is thus closer to the way the digits of numbers are written left-to-right in English, with the most significant digit first, comparing digits to bytes and assuming addresses increase from left to right.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Both types of endianness are in widespread use in digital electronic engineering.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The initial choice of endianness of a new design is often arbitrary, but later technology revisions and updates perpetuate the existing endianness to maintain backward compatibility.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Big-endianness is the dominant ordering in networking protocols, such as in the Internet protocol suite, where it is referred to as *network order*, transmitting the most significant byte first.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Conversely, little-endianness is the dominant ordering for processor architectures (x86, most ARM implementations, base RISC-V implementations) and their associated memory.
[src:bson-format/endianness] File formats can use either ordering; some formats use a mixture of both or contain an indicator of which ordering is used throughout the file.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Endianness is primarily expressed as **big-endian** (BE) or **little-endian** (LE), terms introduced by Danny Cohen in an Internet Experiment Note published in 1980.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Cohen borrowed the terms from an absurd episode in the satirical novel *Gulliver's Travels* by Jonathan Swift.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In the imaginary land of Lilliput, scholars are fiercely divided by a never-ending debate over how correctly to break the shell of a boiled egg.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Those who insist on breaking the big end of the shell are Big-Endians, while their opponents who break the opposite end of the shell are Little-Endians.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Computer memory consists of a sequence of storage cells (smallest addressable units); in machines that support byte addressing, those units are called *bytes*.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Each byte is identified and accessed in hardware and software by its memory address.
[src:bson-format/endianness] If the total number of bytes in memory is *n*, then addresses are enumerated from 0 to *n* − 1.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Computer programs often use data structures or fields that may consist of more data than can be stored in one byte.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In the context of this article, where its type cannot be arbitrarily complicated, a *field* consists of a consecutive sequence of bytes and represents a *simple data value* which, at least potentially, can be manipulated by *one* single hardware instruction.
[src:bson-format/endianness] On most systems, the address of a multi-byte simple data value is the address of its first byte (the byte with the lowest address).
[src:bson-format/endianness] There are exceptions to this rule – for example, the Add instruction of the IBM 1401 addresses variable-length fields at their low-order (highest-addressed) position with their lengths being defined by a word mark set at their high-order (lowest-addressed) position.
[src:bson-format/endianness] When an operation such as addition is performed, the processor begins at the low-order positions at the high addresses of the two fields and works its way down to the high-order.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Another important attribute of a byte being part of a *field* is its *significance*.
[src:bson-format/endianness] These attributes of the parts of a field play an important role in the sequence the bytes are accessed by the computer hardware, more precisely: by the low-level algorithms contributing to the results of a computer instruction.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Positional number systems (mostly base 2, or less often base 10) are the predominant way of representing and particularly of manipulating integer data by computers.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In pure form, this is valid for moderately sized non-negative integers, e.g., of C data type `unsigned`.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In such a number system, the *value* of a digit that contributes to the whole number is determined not only by its value as a single digit, but also by the position it holds in the complete number, called its significance.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In *big-endian* and *little-endian*, the *end* is the extremity where the *big* or *little* significance is written in the location indexed by the lowest memory address.
[src:bson-format/endianness] When character (text) strings are to be compared with one another, e.g., in order to support some mechanism like sorting, this is very frequently done lexicographically where a single positional element (character) also has a positional value.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Lexicographical comparison means almost everywhere: first character ranks highest, as in the telephone book.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Almost all machines that can do this using a single instruction are big-endian or at least mixed-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Integer numbers written as text are always represented most significant digit first in memory, which is similar to big-endian, independently of text direction.
[src:bson-format/endianness] When memory bytes are printed sequentially from left to right (e.g., in a hex dump), little-endian representation of integers has the significance decreasing from right to left.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In other words, it appears backwards when visualized, which can be counterintuitive.
[src:bson-format/endianness] This behavior arises, for example, in FourCC or similar techniques that involve packing characters into an integer, so that it becomes a sequence of specific characters in memory.
[src:bson-format/endianness] For example, take the string "JOHN", stored in hexadecimal ASCII.
[src:bson-format/endianness] On big-endian machines, the value appears left-to-right, coinciding with the correct string order for reading the result ("J O H N").
[src:bson-format/endianness] But on a little-endian machine, one would see "N H O J".
[src:bson-format/endianness] Middle-endian machines complicate this even further; for example, on the PDP-11, a 32-bit float is stored as two 16-bit words "JO" "HN" in big-endian, with the characters in the 16-bit words being stored in little-endian, resulting in "O J N H".
[src:bson-format/endianness] Byte-swapping consists of rearranging bytes to change endianness.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Many compilers provide built-ins that are likely to be compiled into native processor instructions (`bswap`/`movbe`), such as `__builtin_bswap32`.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Some CPU instruction sets provide native support for endian byte swapping, such as `bswap` (x86 — 486 and later, i960 — i960Jx and later), and `rev` (ARMv6 and later).
[src:bson-format/endianness] Some compilers have built-in facilities for byte swapping.
[src:bson-format/endianness] For example, GNU Fortran and the Intel Fortran Compiler both support the non-standard `CONVERT` specifier when opening a file, e.g.: `OPEN(unit, CONVERT='BIG_ENDIAN',...)`.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Other compilers have options for generating code that globally enables the conversion for all file IO operations.
[src:bson-format/endianness] This permits the reuse of code on a system with the opposite endianness without code modification.
[src:bson-format/endianness] For example, a 32-bit memory location with content `4A 00 00 00` can be read at the same address as either 8-bit (value = 4A), 16-bit (004A), 24-bit (00004A), or 32-bit (0000004A), all of which retain the same numeric value.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Although this little-endian property is rarely used directly by high-level programmers, it is occasionally employed by code optimizers as well as by assembly language programmers.
[src:bson-format/endianness] While not allowed by C++, such type punning code is allowed as "implementation-defined" by the C11 standard and commonly used in code interacting with hardware.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Some operations in positional number systems have a natural or preferred order in which the elementary steps are to be executed.
[src:bson-format/endianness] This order may affect their performance on small-scale byte-addressable processors and microcontrollers.
[src:bson-format/endianness] However, high-performance processors usually fetch multi-byte operands from memory in the same amount of time they would have fetched a single byte, so the complexity of the hardware is not affected by the byte ordering.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Addition, subtraction, and multiplication start at the least significant digit position and propagate the carry to the subsequent more significant position.
[src:bson-format/endianness] On most systems, the address of a multi-byte value is the address of its first byte (the byte with the lowest address).
[src:bson-format/endianness] The implementation of these operations is marginally simpler using little-endian machines, where this first byte contains the least significant digit.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Comparison and division start at the most significant digit and propagate a possible carry to the subsequent less significant digits.
[src:bson-format/endianness] For fixed-length numerical values (typically of length 1,2,4,8,16), the implementation of these operations is marginally simpler on big-endian machines.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Some big-endian processors (e.g., the IBM System/360 and its successors) contain hardware instructions for lexicographically comparing varying-length character strings.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The normal data transport by an assignment statement is, in principle, independent of the endianness of the processor.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Many historical and extant processors use a big-endian memory representation, either exclusively or as a design option.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The IBM System/360 uses big-endian byte order, as do its successors System/370, ESA/390, and z/Architecture.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The PDP-10 uses big-endian addressing for byte-oriented instructions.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The IBM Series/1 minicomputer uses big-endian byte order.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The Motorola 6800 / 6801, the 6809 and the 68000 series of processors use the big-endian format.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Solely big-endian architectures include the IBM z/Architecture and OpenRISC.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The PDP-11 minicomputer, however, uses little-endian byte order, as does its VAX successor.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The Datapoint 2200 used simple bit-serial logic with little-endian to facilitate carry propagation.
[src:bson-format/endianness] When Intel developed the 8008 microprocessor for Datapoint, they used little-endian for compatibility.
[src:bson-format/endianness] However, as Intel was unable to deliver the 8008 in time, Datapoint used a medium-scale integration equivalent, but the little-endianness was retained in most Intel designs, including the MCS-48 and the 8086 and its x86 successors, including IA-32 and x86-64 processors.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The MOS Technology 6502 family (including Western Design Center 65802 and 65C816), the Zilog Z80 (including Z180 and eZ80), the Altera Nios II, the Atmel AVR, the Andes Technology NDS32, the Qualcomm Hexagon, and many other processors and processor families are also little-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The Intel 8051, unlike other Intel processors, expects 16-bit addresses for LJMP and LCALL in big-endian format; however, xCALL instructions store the return address onto the stack in little-endian format.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Some instruction set architectures feature a setting which allows for switchable endianness in data fetches and stores, instruction fetches, or both; those instruction set architectures are referred to as *bi-endian*.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Architectures that support switchable endianness include PowerPC/Power ISA, SPARC V9, ARM versions 3 and above, DEC Alpha, MIPS, Intel i860, PA-RISC, SuperH SH-4, IA-64, C-Sky, and RISC-V.
[src:bson-format/endianness] This feature can improve performance or simplify the logic of networking devices and software.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The word *bi-endian*, when said of hardware, denotes the capability of the machine to compute or pass data in either endian format.
[src:bson-format/endianness] IBM AIX and IBM i run in big-endian mode on bi-endian Power ISA; Linux originally ran in big-endian mode, but by 2019, IBM had transitioned to little-endian mode for Linux to ease the porting of Linux software from x86 to Power.
[src:bson-format/endianness] SPARC has no relevant little-endian deployment, as both Oracle Solaris and Linux run in big-endian mode on bi-endian SPARC systems, and can be considered big-endian in practice.
[src:bson-format/endianness] ARM, C-Sky, and RISC-V have no relevant big-endian deployments and can be considered little-endian in practice.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The term *bi-endian* refers primarily to how a processor treats data accesses.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Instruction accesses (fetches of instruction words) on a given processor may still assume a fixed endianness, even if data accesses are fully bi-endian, though this is not always the case, such as on Intel's IA-64-based Itanium CPU, which allows both.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Some nominally bi-endian CPUs require motherboard help to fully switch endianness.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In the absence of this unusual motherboard hardware, device driver software must write to different addresses to undo the incomplete transformation and also must perform a normal byte swap.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Some CPUs, such as many PowerPC processors intended for embedded use and almost all SPARC processors, allow per-page choice of endianness.
[src:bson-format/endianness] SPARC processors since the late 1990s (SPARC v9 compliant processors) allow data endianness to be chosen with each individual instruction that loads from or stores to memory.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The ARM architecture supports two big-endian modes, called *BE-8* and *BE-32*.
[src:bson-format/endianness] CPUs up to ARMv5 only support BE-32 or word-invariant mode.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Here, any naturally aligned 32-bit access works like in little-endian mode, but access to a byte or 16-bit word is redirected to the corresponding address and unaligned access is not allowed.
[src:bson-format/endianness] ARMv6 introduces BE-8 or byte-invariant mode, where access to a single byte works as in little-endian mode, but accessing a 16-bit, 32-bit or (starting with ARMv8) 64-bit word results in a byte swap of the data.
[src:bson-format/endianness] This simplifies unaligned memory access as well as memory-mapped access to registers other than 32-bit.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Many processors have instructions to convert a word in a register to the opposite endianness, that is, they swap the order of the bytes in a 16-, 32- or 64-bit word.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Recent Intel x86 and x86-64 architecture CPUs have a MOVBE instruction (Intel Core since generation 4, after Atom), which fetches a big-endian format word from memory or writes a word into memory in big-endian format.
[src:bson-format/endianness] These processors are otherwise thoroughly little-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] There are also devices that use different formats in different places.
[src:bson-format/endianness] For instance, the BQ27421 Texas Instruments battery gauge uses the little-endian format for its registers and the big-endian format for its random-access memory.
[src:bson-format/endianness] SPARC historically used big-endian until version 9, which is bi-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Similarly, early IBM POWER processors were big-endian, but the PowerPC and Power ISA descendants are now bi-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The ARM architecture was little-endian before version 3, when it became bi-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Although many processors use little-endian storage for all types of data (integer, floating point), there are a number of hardware architectures where floating-point numbers are represented in big-endian form while integers are represented in little-endian form.
[src:bson-format/endianness] There are ARM processors that have mixed-endian floating-point representation for double-precision numbers: each of the two 32-bit words is stored as little-endian, but the most significant word is stored first.
[src:bson-format/endianness] VAX floating point stores little-endian 16-bit words in big-endian order.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Because there have been many floating-point formats with no network standard representation for them, the XDR standard uses big-endian IEEE 754 as its representation.
[src:bson-format/endianness] It may therefore appear strange that the widespread IEEE 754 floating-point standard does not specify endianness.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Theoretically, this means that even standard IEEE floating-point data written by one machine might not be readable by another.
[src:bson-format/endianness] However, on modern standard computers (i.e., implementing IEEE 754), one may safely assume that the endianness is the same for floating-point numbers as for integers, making the conversion straightforward regardless of data type.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Small embedded systems using special floating-point formats may be another matter, however.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Most instructions considered so far contain the size (lengths) of their operands within the operation code.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Frequently available operand lengths are 1, 2, 4, 8, or 16 bytes.
[src:bson-format/endianness] But there are also architectures where the length of an operand may be held in a separate field of the instruction or with the operand itself, e.g., by means of a word mark.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Such an approach allows operand lengths up to 256 bytes or larger.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The data types of such operands are character strings or BCD.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Machines able to manipulate such data with one instruction (e.g. compare, add) include the IBM 1401, 1410, 1620, System/360, System/370, ESA/390, and z/Architecture, all of them of type big-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Numerous other orderings, generically called *middle-endian* or *mixed-endian*, are possible.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The PDP-11 is primarily a 16-bit little-endian system.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The instructions to convert between floating-point and integer values in the optional floating-point processor of the PDP-11/45, PDP-11/70, and in some later processors, stored 32-bit *double precision integer long* values with the 16-bit halves swapped from the expected little-endian order.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The UNIX C compiler used the same format for 32-bit long integers.
[src:bson-format/endianness] UNIX was one of the first systems to allow the same code to be compiled for platforms with different internal representations.
[src:bson-format/endianness] One of the first programs converted was supposed to print out `Unix`, but on the Series/1 it printed `nUxi` instead.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Segment descriptors of IA-32 and compatible processors keep a 32-bit base address of the segment stored in little-endian order, but in four nonconsecutive bytes, at relative positions 2, 3, 4 and 7 of the descriptor start.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Hardware description languages (HDLs) used to express digital logic often support arbitrary endianness, with arbitrary granularity.
[src:bson-format/endianness] For example, in SystemVerilog, a word can be defined as little-endian or big-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The recognition of endianness is important when reading a file or filesystem created on a computer with different endianness.
[src:bson-format/endianness] An attempt to read such a file using Fortran on a system of the other endianness results in a run-time error, because the count fields are incorrect.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Unicode text can optionally start with a byte order mark (BOM) to signal the endianness of the file or stream.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In UTF-32 for example, a big-endian file should start with `00 00 FE FF`; a little-endian should start with `FF FE 00 00`.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Application binary data formats, such as MATLAB *.mat* files, or the *.bil* data format, used in topography, are usually endianness-independent.
[src:bson-format/endianness] This is achieved by storing the data always in one fixed endianness or carrying with the data a switch to indicate the endianness.
[src:bson-format/endianness] An example of the former is the binary XLS file format that is portable between Windows and Mac systems and always little-endian, requiring the Mac application to swap the bytes on load and save when running on a big-endian Motorola 68K or PowerPC processor.
[src:bson-format/endianness] TIFF image files are an example of the second strategy, whose header instructs the application about the endianness of their internal binary integers.
[src:bson-format/endianness] If a file starts with the signature `MM` it means that integers are represented as big-endian, while `II` means little-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Those signatures need a single 16-bit word each, and they are palindromes, so they are endianness independent.
[src:bson-format/endianness] `I` stands for Intel and `M` stands for Motorola.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Intel CPUs are little-endian, while Motorola 680x0 CPUs are big-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] This explicit signature allows a TIFF reader program to swap bytes if necessary when a given file was generated by a TIFF writer program running on a computer with a different endianness.
[src:bson-format/endianness] ZFS, which combines a filesystem and a logical volume manager, is known to provide adaptive endianness and to work with both big-endian and little-endian systems.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Many IETF RFCs use the term *network order*, meaning the order of transmission for bytes *over the wire* in network protocols.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Among others, the historic RFC 1700 defines the network order for protocols in the Internet protocol suite to be big-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] However, not all protocols use big-endian byte order as the network order.
[src:bson-format/endianness] The Server Message Block (SMB) protocol uses little-endian byte order.
[src:bson-format/endianness] In CANopen, multi-byte parameters are always sent least significant byte first (little-endian).
[src:bson-format/endianness] The same is true for Ethernet Powerlink.
[src:bson-format/endianness] These functions may be a no-op on a big-endian system.
[src:bson-format/endianness] While the high-level network protocols usually consider the byte (mostly meant as *octet*) as their atomic unit, the lowest layers of a network stack may deal with the ordering of bits within a byte.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Bit ordering is sometimes referred to as little-endian or big-endian.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Bit ordering does not need to be the same as byte ordering.
[src:bson-format/endianness] For example, RS-232 transmits bits least significant first, I2C transmits bits most significant first, and SPI can be sent in either order.
[src:bson-format/endianness] Ethernet transmits individual bits least significant first, but bytes are sent big-endian.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The American software company 10gen began developing MongoDB in 2007 as a component of a planned platform-as-a-service product.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] In 2009, the company shifted to an open-source development model and began offering commercial support and other services.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] In 2013, 10gen changed its name to MongoDB Inc.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] On October 20, 2017, MongoDB became a publicly traded company, listed on NASDAQ as MDB with an IPO price of $24 per share.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] On November 8, 2018, with the stable release 4.0.4, the software's license changed from AGPL 3.0 to SSPL.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] On October 30, 2019, MongoDB teamed with Alibaba Cloud to offer Alibaba Cloud customers a MongoDB-as-a-service solution.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Customers can use the managed offering from Alibaba's global data centers.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] In December 2025, a major exploit was discovered and titled as "MongoBleed".
[src:bson-format/mongodb] This exploit led to the compromise of many corporate servers.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] As of May 2025, MongoDB was the fifth most popular database software.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] It focuses mostly on managing large databases of unstructured, "messy" data.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] It's typically used for mobile and web apps that commonly use unstructured databases.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] As of 2024, there were 50,000 MongoDB customers.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB was originally best known as a NoSQL database product.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The company released a database as-a-service product called Atlas in 2016 that became 70 percent of MongoDB's revenue by 2024.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Over time, MongoDB added analytics, transactional databases, encryption, vector databases, ACID, migration features, and other enterprise tools.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Initially, the MongoDB software was free and open source under the AGPL license.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB adopted an SSPL (server side public license) for future releases starting in 2018.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB implements its own query language called *Mongo Query Language* (MQL).
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB supports field, range query and regular-expression searches.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Queries can return specific fields of documents and also include user-defined JavaScript functions.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Queries can also be configured to return a random sample of results of a given size.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Fields in a MongoDB document can be indexed with primary and secondary indices.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB provides high availability with replica sets.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] A replica set consists of two or more copies of the data.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Each replica-set member may act in the role of primary or secondary replica at any time.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] All writes and reads are done on the primary replica by default.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Secondary replicas maintain a copy of the data of the primary using built-in replication.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] When a primary replica fails, the replica set automatically conducts an election process to determine which secondary should become the primary.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Secondaries can optionally serve read operations, but that data is only eventually consistent by default.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] If the replicated MongoDB deployment only has a single secondary member, a separate daemon called an arbiter must be added to the set.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] It has the single responsibility of resolving the election of the new primary.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] As a consequence, an ideal distributed MongoDB deployment requires at least three separate servers, even in the case of just one primary and one secondary.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB scales horizontally using sharding.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The user chooses a shard key, which determines how the data in a collection will be distributed.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The data is split into ranges (based on the shard key) and distributed across multiple shards, which are masters with one or more replicas.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Alternatively, the shard key can be hashed to map to a shard – enabling an even data distribution.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB can run over multiple servers, balancing the load or duplicating data to keep the system functional in case of hardware failure.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB can be used as a file system, called GridFS, with load-balancing and data-replication features over multiple machines for storing files.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] This function, called a grid file system, is included with MongoDB drivers.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB exposes functions for file manipulation and content to developers.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] GridFS can be accessed using the mongofiles utility or plugins for Nginx and lighttpd.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] GridFS divides a file into parts, or chunks, and stores each of those chunks as a separate document.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB provides three ways to perform aggregation: the aggregation pipeline (preferred), the map-reduce function (deprecated as of MongoDB 5.0) and single-purpose aggregation methods.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Map-reduce can be used for batch processing of data and aggregation operations.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] However, according to MongoDB's documentation, the aggregation pipeline provides better performance for most aggregation operations.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The aggregation framework enables users to obtain results similar to those returned by queries that include the SQL GROUP BY clause.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Aggregation operators can be strung together to form a pipeline, analogous to Unix pipes.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The aggregation framework includes the $lookup operator, which can join documents from multiple collections, as well as statistical operators such as standard deviation.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB supports fixed-size collections called capped collections.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] This type of collection maintains insertion order and, once the specified size has been reached, behaves like a circular queue.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB supports multi-document ACID transactions since the 4.0 release in June 2018.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] As of October 2018, MongoDB is released under the Server Side Public License (SSPL), a non-free license developed by the project.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] It replaces the GNU Affero General Public License.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] In contrast to the AGPL, the SSPL prevents anyone but MongoDB Inc. from making MongoDB "available as a service" without negotiating a separate license from MongoDb Inc.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The license text specifies a condition for making MongoDB which MongoDB Inc. has claimed to be similar to AGPL, but is actually impossible to comply with.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The condition states that "all programs that you use to make the Program" ...
[src:bson-format/mongodb] "available as a service" must be published under the SSPL.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] However, a core component of MongoDB called WiredTiger is licensed as GPL, and the GPL does not allow redistribution under any license except the GPL.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] This does not apply to the copyright holder (MongoDB Inc.).
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Since MongoDB's SSPL adoption in 2018, no one has ever provided MongoDB as a paid service under the SSPL license (including MongoDB Inc.).
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The SSPL was submitted for certification to the Open Source Initiative but later withdrawn.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] In January 2021, the Open Source Initiative stated that SSPL is not an open source license.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The language drivers are available under an Apache License.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] In addition, MongoDB Inc. offers proprietary licenses for MongoDB.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The last versions licensed as AGPL version 3 are 4.0.3 (stable) and 4.1.4.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] MongoDB has been removed from the Debian, Fedora and Red Hat Enterprise Linux distributions because of the licensing change.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Fedora determined that the SSPL version 1 is not a free software license because it is "intentionally crafted to be aggressively discriminatory" towards commercial users.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Because of MongoDB's default security configuration, which allows any user full access to the database, data from tens of thousands of MongoDB installations has been stolen.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Furthermore, many MongoDB servers have been held for ransom.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] In September 2017, Davi Ottenheimer head of product security at MongoDB, proclaimed that measures had been taken to defend against these risks.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] In some failure scenarios in which an application can access two distinct MongoDB processes that cannot access each other, it is possible for MongoDB to return stale reads.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] It is also possible for MongoDB to roll back writes that have been acknowledged.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The issue was addressed in version 3.4.0, released in November 2016, and applied to earlier releases from v3.2.12 onward.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Before version 2.2, locks were implemented on a per-server-process basis.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] With version 2.2, locks were implemented at the database level.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Beginning with version 3.0, pluggable storage engines are available, and each storage engine may implement locks differently.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] With MongoDB 3.0, locks are implemented at the collection level for the MMAPv1 storage engine, while the WiredTiger storage engine uses an optimistic concurrency protocol that effectively provides document-level locking.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Even with versions prior to 3.0, one approach to increase concurrency is to use sharding.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] In some situations, reads and writes will yield their locks.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] If MongoDB predicts that a page is unlikely to be in memory, operations will yield their lock while the pages load.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The use of lock yielding expanded greatly in version 2.2.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Until version 3.3.11, MongoDB could not perform collation-based sorting and was limited to bytewise comparison via memcmp, which would not provide correct ordering for many non-English languages when used with a Unicode encoding.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Prior to MongoDB 4.0, queries against an index were not atomic.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] Documents that were updated while queries was running could be missed.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] The introduction of the snapshot read concern in MongoDB 4.0 eliminated this risk.
[src:bson-format/mongodb] FerretDB is an open source project that converts MongoDB 5.0 wire protocol queries into SQL, allowing clients to query postgreSQL (or other databases) using the Mongo wire protocol.
[src:bson-format/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:bson-format/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:bson-format/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:bson-format/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:bson-format/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:bson-format/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:bson-format/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:bson-format/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:bson-format/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:bson-format/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:bson-format/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:bson-format/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:bson-format/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:bson-format/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:bson-format/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:bson-format/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:bson-format/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:bson-format/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:bson-format/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:bson-format/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:bson-format/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:bson-format/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:bson-format/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:bson-format/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:bson-format/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:bson-format/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:bson-format/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:bson-format/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:bson-format/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:bson-format/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:bson-format/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:bson-format/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:bson-format/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:bson-format/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:bson-format/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:bson-format/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:bson-format/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:bson-format/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:bson-format/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:bson-format/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:bson-format/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:bson-format/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:bson-format/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:bson-format/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:bson-format/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:bson-format/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:bson-format/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:bson-format/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:bson-format/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:bson-format/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:bson-format/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:bson-format/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:bson-format/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:bson-format/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:bson-format/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:bson-format/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:bson-format/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:bson-format/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:bson-format/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:bson-format/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:bson-format/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:bson-format/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:bson-format/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:bson-format/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:bson-format/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:bson-format/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:bson-format/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:bson-format/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:bson-format/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:bson-format/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:bson-format/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:bson-format/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:bson-format/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:bson-format/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:bson-format/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:bson-format/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:bson-format/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:bson-format/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:bson-format/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:bson-format/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:bson-format/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:bson-format/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:bson-format/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:bson-format/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:bson-format/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
